<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>BF-1 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers solving linear and quadratic equations.  You will be given 2-3 problems in this 
      outcome; a linear equation and two quadratic equations.  The linear equation will be solved using 
      the standard algebraic techniques, while the quadratic equations will be solved using factoring, the 
      extraction of roots method, completing the square or the quadratic formula.  You should be able 
      to write out complete steps to solve these types of problems by hand, without the use of a calculator.
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 3 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Linear Equations: Solve linear equations using algebraic techniques.</p></li>
      <li><p>Quadratic Equations: Solve quadratic equations using factoring, the extraction 
        of roots method, completing the square or the quadratic formula.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the following equation: <m>\frac{2}{3}x+\frac{5}{18}=x-\frac{4}{9}</m> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>Start by using the LCD to clear the fractions. Then combine like terms and solve.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=\frac{13}{6}</m></p></answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Start by using the LCD of 18 to clear the fractions: <m>12x+5=18x-8</m>. Then combine 
          like terms: <m>5+8=18x-12x</m>. Next, simplify to get the solution: <m>x=\frac{13}{6}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the following equation: <m>3(2x-7)-4x+1=5x-2(x+3)</m> 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>Start by distributing over the parentheses and then combining like terms.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=-14</m></p></answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Start by distributing over the parentheses: <m>6x-21-4x+1=5x-2x-6</m>. Then combine 
          like terms: <m>2x-20=3x-6</m>. Next, move all terms to one side: <m>-20+6=x</m>. 
          Finally, simplify to get the solution: <m>x=-14</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>Solve <m>8x^2-18x+9=0</m> by factoring.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>Look for two numbers that multiply to give the product of the coefficient of x^2 and the constant term, and add up to give the coefficient of x.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=\frac{3}{4}</m> and <m>x=\frac{3}{2}</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>
        Start by multiplying the leading coefficient and the constant: <m>8\cdot 9=72</m>. Find the
      two factors of 72 that add up to -18: -12 and -6. Rewrite the middle term using these factors:
      <m>8x^2-12x-6x+9=0</m>. Factor by grouping: <m>4x(2x-3)-3(2x-3)=0</m>. Factor out the common 
      binomial: <m>(4x-3)(2x-3)=0</m>. Set each factor equal to zero and solve for x: <m>x=\frac{3}{4}</m> 
      and <m>x=\frac{3}{2}</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>Solve <m>(6x-5)^2=49</m> using the extraction of roots method.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>Take the square root of both sides and solve the resulting linear equations.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=2</m> and <m>x=\frac{-1}{3}</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>
        Start by taking the square root of both sides of the equation: <m>6x-5=\pm 7</m>. 
        Then solve the resulting linear equations: <m>6x-5=7</m> and <m>6x-5=-7</m>. This gives 
        <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=\frac{-1}{3}</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>Solve <m>4y^2+8y-5=5</m> using the quadratic formula.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>First, move all terms to one side to get the equation in standard form, then apply the quadratic formula.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=\frac{-1\pm\sqrt{14}}{2}</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>
        Start by setting the equation equal to zero and finding the terms: <m>a=4</m>, <m>b=8</m>, 
        and <m>c=-10</m>. Then apply the quadratic formula by plugging these values into 
        <m>x=\frac{-b\pm\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a}</m>. <m>x=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{64-4(4)(-10)}}{2(4)}</m>. Simplify 
        inside the root <m>x=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{64+160}}{8}</m>. <m>x=\frac{-8\pm\sqrt{224}}{8}</m>. Now we 
        can simplify the root <m>x=\frac{-8\pm 4\sqrt{14}}{8}</m>. Then simplify the resulting expression: 
        <m>x=\frac{-1\pm\sqrt{14}}{2}</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <statement>
        <p>Solve <m>3x^2+4x-5=0</m> by completing the square.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint><p>First, divide by factor out the coefficient of x^2, then move the constant 
        term to the other side, and complete the square.</p></hint>
      <answer><p><m>x=\frac{-2\pm\sqrt{19}}{3}</m></p></answer>
      <solution><p>Since the leading coefficient isn't one, start by factoring out the coefficient from
        the x-terms and move the constant term to the other side. <m>3(x^2+\frac{4}{3}x)=5</m>. Next, 
        complete the square by adding the square of half the coefficient of x to both sides: 
        <m>3(x^2+\frac{4}{3}x+\frac{4}{9})=5+3\left(\frac{4}{9}\right)</m>. This gives us 
        <m>3(x+\frac{2}{3})^2=\frac{19}{3}</m>. Now we can divide by 3 and take the square root of 
        both sides: <m>x+\frac{2}{3}=\pm\sqrt{\frac{19}{9}}</m>. Finally, solve for x to get the 
        solution: <m>x=\frac{-2\pm\sqrt{19}}{3}</m>.
      </p></solution>
    </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>
